    <Folder>
      <name>Intelligence Summary</name>
      <Placemark>
        <name>AI Council Assessment</name>
        <styleUrl>#intel</styleUrl>
        <description>The synthesized intelligence data reveals a sustained focus on global logistics and support operations, with US military airlift assets—primarily C-17 and C-130 aircraft—conducting routine but critical missions across multiple theaters. European airspace shows a particularly high density of transport and ISR activity, including Dassault Falcon platforms (6X and 7X) conducting intelligence-gathering operations, likely in support of NATO or US strategic interests. The Indo-Pacific and Mediterranean regions also feature prominently, with C-130 and C-30J platforms supporting logistics, maritime security, and humanitarian assistance. The presence of a KC-135R tanker suggests ongoing aerial refueling operations, likely enabling long-range transport or combat missions. Naval activity is limited in this dataset, with only two vessels explicitly mentioned: USS Rafael Peralta (DDG-115) and USS Tripoli (LHA-7), deployed together in the Philippine Sea. This suggests either a temporary reduction in visible naval deployments or a shift toward more dispersed or covert operations. The lack of US Navy vessel data for high-tension regions such as the South China Sea and Strait of Hormuz is notable and may indicate a period of reduced overt naval presence or a transition to more covert or distributed operations. Overall, the data suggests a steady state of military activity with no immediate indicators of escalation, but the concentration of ISR platforms in Europe and logistics assets in the Indo-Pacific reflects ongoing strategic priorities in those regions. The absence of additional naval deployments in the dataset may warrant further monitoring to determine if this reflects a deliberate operational posture or a gap in positional tracking.</description>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>0,0,0</coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
